<br>
I have been an sf fan for over 40 years, though, and I have a pretty good idea what makes this genre tick, even if I can't articulate it very well. <br>
My favorite definition of science fiction comes from <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.pjfarmer.com">Philip Jose Farmer</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, as a character in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>To Your Scattered Bodies Go</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->: &quot;Science fiction is one of those things which does not exist but which nevertheless has a name.&quot; <br>
Some of my choices are simply my judgment of the best individual work in a series that I think collectively represents a leading work in the field. These are so indicated. <br>
This is my list:<br>
<br>
1. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>War of the Worlds</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, H.G. Wells<br>
2. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Mission of Gravity</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Hal Clement<br>
3. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Moon is a Harsh Mistress</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, Robert Heinlein<br>
4. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Foundation and Empire</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, Isaac Isamov (<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Foundation</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> series)<br>
5. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Childhood's End</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, Arthur C. Clarke<br>
6. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Swords of Zinjaban</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, L. Sprague deCamp (<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Krishna</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> series)<br>
7. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>To Your Scattered Bodies Go</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, Philip Jose Farmer (<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Riverworld</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> series)<br>
8. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Lucifer's Hammer</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, Larry Niven and Jerry Pournelle<br>
9. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Worldwar: In the Balance</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, Harry Turtledove (<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Worldwar</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> series)<br>
10. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Word for World is Forest</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, Ursula K. LeGuin  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A> at: 6/25/03 10:26 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=drcarstairs>DrCarstairs</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Utterly Mad Scientist</span><br>  Posts: 226<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/27/03 1:03 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.angelfire.com/rant/AVitW/images/bioh.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Top Ten Science Fiction Novels</span><hr size=1> Great list AC. I haven’t read all of those books (shame on me). Here is my take on the top ten:<br>
<br>
1 - War of the Worlds – H. G. Wells<br>
2 - 20,000 Leagues Under the Sea - Jules Verne<br>
3 – Foundation and Empire – Isaac Azimov<br>
4 - Second Stage Lensmen - E. E. &quot;Doc&quot; Smith<br>
5 - The Voyage of the Space Beagle - A. E. van Vogt<br>
6 - Warlord of Mars - Edgar Rice Burroughs<br>
7 - The Martian Chronicles – Ray Bradbury<br>
8 - Space Viking – H. Beam Piper<br>
9 - Ringworld – Larry Niven <br>
10 – Childhoods End – Author C. Clark  <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/alien.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
Dr. Carstairs</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomoftenacity>AtomOfTenacity </A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 107<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/27/03 2:05 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/atom_of_tenacity.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Top Ten Science Fiction Novels</span><hr size=1> I read <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Childhood's End</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Enders Game</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in highschool but besides these two books and haven't read one scrap of SF. This is because I am too much of a realist and SF tends to turn me off. I'd rather read books like <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Case for Mars</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Project Orion</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> as I find them easier to relate to. <br>
One of the best books that I ever read non-fiction was <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Entering Space</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> by Dr. Robert Zubrin and reading this book is the cheif reason that I am here today posting on this message board. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 263<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/27/03 3:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Top Ten Science Fiction Novels</span><hr size=1> At the risk of belaboring the obvious, Atom, two books are  hardly a representative sample. <br>
I have dealt with the reality of aerospace technology at a very intimate level all my life, and my enjoyment of SF has not suffered at all from it. <br>
Besides, the concepts in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Case for Mars</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Project Orion</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Entering Space</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> would have been regarded as science fiction within living memory. Many reject them as unrealistic to this day, preferring such things as commercial television, utopian politics, or attempts to commune with whales and spirits. <br>
Verne's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>From the Earth to the Moon</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is scarcely realistic, and wasn't realistic when it was written in the 1860s, yet a strikingly high percentage of the spaceflight pioneers have cited it specifically as a major influence on the genesis of their ideas. <br>
Goddard, Oberth, and von Braun all mentioned it as such. <br>
In a sense, SF is the question and spaceflight is the answer. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomoftenacity>AtomOfTenacity </A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 108<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/27/03 8:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/atom_of_tenacity.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Top Ten Science Fiction Novels</span><hr size=1> <br>
<br>
What I meant by listing those two books was that I read them and wasn’t thrilled about SF. I think that I have started other SF books but was turned off as well.<br>
Now, I did enjoy <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>1984</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> a great deal and I just started reading <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Brave New World</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> a few days ago. But I don’t think that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>1984</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> can really be called SF even though many say otherwise. As for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>BNW</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, it’s too early to tell one way or another. <br>
Oh yeah I just remembered what other book I read: <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Starship Troopers</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> but I can say that the movie was a hell of a lot better then the book. I actually took a SF class in highschool my senior year that qualified as English credit but at the time I didn’t like SF at all. <br>
I remember that we were supposed to read books like <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Dune</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and such but I didn’t do any reading or homework assignments and I ended up getting a D in that class.<br>
