<br>
I never liked <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Dune</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> myself, too murky and ideologically pretentious, with some rather poorly disguised political advocacy thrown in. In very basic terms, it seemed hostile to science and technology rather than supportive of them. In that respect it is more typical of movie/tv sci-fi than of the written variety. <br>
The 1985 <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Dune</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> movie was a knockout visually, perfectly capturing the dark, baroque atmosphere of the book, but the story and editing were a complete disaster. The thing was incomprehensible. Disney later produced a &quot;short&quot; version with a lot of animation and narration thrown in to help make some sense of it all. I did have a lot of fun coming up with parody titles for Dune sequels, since there seemed to be an endless number of these, each weirder and more self-absorbed than the last. <br>
<br>
As for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Starship Troopers</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, the book and movie don't have enough in common for a comparison. I enjoyed the movie more, but it has been quite a while since I read the book. The book is a period piece, written in 1958, and it may well be a product of Robert Heinlein's own midlife crisis (he was 50 that year.) It was deliberately shocking in its positive portrayal of a basically militaristic society. <br>
The movie has a great deal more humor than the book, and actually bears a more than passing resemblance to Harry Harrison's space war satire, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Bill the Galactic Hero.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> The simple-minded interpret the movie as mocking militarism, a dead horse if there ever was one, but I see it more as a satire of war movies in general, and especially of the recycled 60s sensibilities underlying many of these. <br>
One scene is especially telling: the tough drill sergeant challenges the trainees to take him on in hand to hand combat. A big kid accepts and the sergeant duly breaks his arm. At that point, a tough street girl recruit appears and accepts the challenge. According to the current Hollywood paradigm, the girl is supposed to strike a blow for feminism, ala <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>GI Jane</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Aliens</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and whip the loutish sergeant. Instead though, the sergeant leaves her unconcious after a brief struggle.<br>
Another reversal is the scene in which the captured brain-bug is dragged from its cave and the clairvoyant colonel attempts to communicate with it. He makes contact, then solemnly announces to a crowd of soldiers that &quot;it's afraid.&quot; <br>
This is a perfect setup for a &quot;moment of recognition&quot;, a moth-eaten cliche of war movies, the time when the protagonist realizes that the demonized enemy is really just like himself. In SST, however, the assembled soldiers cheer triumphantly and there is great joy at the news that the hated bug fears them.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 265<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/27/03 10:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Top Ten Science Fiction Novels</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Dune</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> sequel parody titles:<br>
